								style="text-align:left ;margin-inline-end: 4%;margin-inline-start: 4%;padding: 2.5px 2.5px 2.5px 2.5px; margin-block-start:2%;">

In this figure, we show the importance and impact of people relations in the corporate network. The figure on the left hand side shows the company-subsidiary network, which only consists of owner companies, and the companies held by them (subsidiaries). An owner and a subsidiary are connected by an edge. The figure on the right hand side shows the same network, but this time with also people connections. In this network, we have connections between owners and subsidiaries as before. But alongside, we also have connections between companies if they share some common board members between them. We call these connections "people connections".
<br><br>
We can see here that the company-subsidiary network is very sparse, showing few connections and a low density. But as soon as we add the people connections in this network, it becomes much denser. We have also shown the politically connected companies (in both figures) as the bigger, blue nodes. These findings indicate towards two points: 
<br><br>
1. Most of the interlocks between companies occur through people connections, or by way of common board memberships. <br>
2. Many of the politically connected companies are mostly located towards the dense core of the network, i.e., many of the politically connected companies are also highly connected with other companies and may hold &nbsp; considerable network power. <br><br>


