								style="text-align:left ;margin-inline-end: 4%;margin-inline-start: 4%;padding: 2.5px 2.5px 2.5px 2.5px; margin-block-start:2%;">
								We have created an indicator of corporate government overlap, which reflects how much
								the corporate and government networks overlap. This indicator empirically measures the
								number and strength of edges between the two networks and calculates a single score that
								represents the strength of overlap between them. In the above figure, we plot this score
								over the period of four Lok Sabha elections.<br><br>
								We consider companies and their managers to be the part of the corporate network, and
								the politicians and bureaucrats (IAS officers) to be a part of the government network.
								An overlap between these two networks occurs in the form of bridge edges, i.e., edges
								that connect the two networks. Some examples of bridge edges include: a politician who
								is connected to a company as a manager, a politician whose relative is the manager of a
								company, etc. Our index measures the number and strength of such bridge edges. <br><br>
								As we can see, the indicator of overlap increases over time. This means that the
								corporate and government worlds are increasingly getting interconnected, and over the
								years, this interconnection is increasing. Quite often, the flow of benefits between the
								corporate and government worlds manifests itself through these bridges.<br><br>
								Data sources: The data to build the network was obtained from different web sources. The
								corporate data was obtained from the websites of ministry of corporate affairs (MCA),
								and Bombay Stock Exchange (for public listed companies). The politician data was
								obtained from India votes (Lok Sabha), and Wikipedia (Rajya Sabha and Prime/Chief
								Ministers data). The bureaucrat data was obtained from Persmin (shared with us by Ashoka
								university). The corporate network includes the BSE public listed companies, their
								directors and managers, and a 1-hop neighbourhood of other companies and people to whom
								this network is linked. The government network includes politicians who contested the
								Lok Sabha elections for the years 2004, 2009, and 2014, IAS bureaucrats during the
								period 1961 to 2017. The corporate network includes companies and their managers formed
								since 1980 till date.
							</p>
